<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,430,1897,1924]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
The 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Reiche &amp; Saulcy" baseAuthorityYear="1855" box="[207,345,1898,1924]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Nebrioporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laeviventris">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,345,1898,1924]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">laeviventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1435,1971,2036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">As here defined, this is the second most speciose group. The distributional range extends from the Eastern Mediterranean seaboard, eastward to the southern slopes of Himalayas; most species are known from Eastern</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1436,152,216]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Mediterranean and Middle East. Many occupy warm and arid regions and in all likelihood are adapted to survive long periods of drought. Four subgroups are here recognised.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
